<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.netdesign.net/~tina/Luna/EQ/story1.html">The Face of Erollisi</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.netdesign.net/~tina/Luna/EQ/story1.html">The Swindler</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.netdesign.net/~tina/Luna/EQ/story1.html">The Apprentice</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
My stomach twists within me as the waves crash against this unnamed barge.  I <br>
feel trapped, surrounded as I am by water.  Captured as I am by Teir'dal.<br>
<br>
I wince as I remember the events of the day.  I following Devago around like<br>
dutiful hound.  He played with me, politely asking if I would like to journey<br>
with him accross the ocean, knowing full well I would say yes by the force of<br>
his magics.<br>
<br>
The boat we boarded, this boat, was small, plain, and looked barely seaworthy.<br>
The captain and crew, entirely human save one ill tempered halfling, looked<br>
to be in similarly poor shape.  The head watchman at the docks seemed glad<br>
to see us go.<br>
<br>
We had barely left the docks when Devago dropped his guise, and appeared before<br>
me in his true dark elven form.  Even under the influence of his charms, I<br>
remember being surprised.  Once the last glimpse of Freeport had vanished into<br>
the sea, he purged his enchantment from me, and laughed in view of my fear<br>
and horror at my plight.  I quickly regained my composure though, and took on <br>
a stoic countenance.  I would not give him that pleasure.<br>
<br>
&quot;If you will kill me, then do it now,&quot; I said.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, no, M'lady, that would be a crime against my art,&quot; he said chuckling.<br>
You will serve me in my art, willingly or not.  Over time though, I am sure<br>
it will be willingly.<br>
<br>
&quot;I will never serve a child of hate,&quot; I stated.  &quot;You may enslave my mind, but<br>
my spirit belongs to Erollisi Marr, and at my first chance I will escape you,<br>
even if my escape is into death.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;As you wish,&quot; he replied calmly, &quot;go now if you will, the sharks will make<br>
short work of you.&quot;<br>
<br>
I ran to the side of the boat and peered out at the water.  My heart pounded<br>
in my chest, I did not know how to swim.  Were there really sharks? It would<br>
not matter, there was no where for me to go.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why do you want my help?&quot; I asked.  &quot;Your kind, if you really are Teir'dal,<br>
hates mine.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I care little for the tirades and wars of my race,&quot; he replied moving up<br>
behind me.  &quot;I care for power.  While it was simple enough for me to enslave<br>
your mind, Luna, there is much more for me to learn, and my development <br>
will be facilitated by a willing apprentice.  My own kin are untrustworthy <br>
and arrogant.  Humans are blunt and simple, though I was prepared to<br>
accept that.  But, then you came along, and I saw in a moment your affinity<br>
for the art.&quot;  He placed his hand on my shoulder, and I cringed.  &quot;I can<br>
sense even know that while I repulse you, my power intrigues you.&quot;  He<br>
chuckled.  &quot;The irony of you serving me appeals to me as well.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The only power that intrigues me is the power of Erollisi,&quot; I replied.<br>
While I longed to scratch at his hand, for daring to touch me, I knew<br>
that was a pointless exercise.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your lies are simple to see though.  Why can you not accept your failure<br>
as a priestess and move on? How many years will you waste in that temple,<br>
waiting for the call that will never come?&quot;<br>
<br>
My cheeks burned with embarassment.  While under his lure he had questioned<br>
me thoroughly and I had told him everything of my life, from seeing the<br>
face of Erollisi, to my years as a lay priestess.  &quot;My day will come,<br>
I will ascend.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That day is now,&quot; he replied. &quot;You will ascend under me.  I care not if <br>
you cling to your God, though it is a weakness and not a strength I assure<br>
you.  You can not deny the art. It is part of you, and it will be <br>
awakened.  I will awaken it.  It is your destiny, and mine.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You will kill me when you are done with me.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Perhaps.  Perhaps not.  We will see.&quot;<br>
<br>
It was then I decided to play along with him, and watch for my chance for<br>
escape.<br>
